        content: 'EU import-export trading companies selling to international customers face elevated credit risk compared to domestic trade, due to: greater difficulty in assessing buyer financial strength across jurisdictions, reduced legal enforceability of claims across borders, and longer resolution timelines if disputes arise.\n\nCredit insurance — insuring export receivables against buyer insolvency or protracted default — is used by many EU trading companies to protect against catastrophic bad debt from significant buyers. EU export credit agencies (national ECAs such as UKEF, Euler Hermes, Atradius, and Coface) and private insurers offer credit insurance for EU exporters. Premiums of 0.2–0.8% of insured receivables are justified for material single-buyer exposures.\n\nEU trading companies should assess each customer\'s payment risk before extending credit: credit reference agency checks, trade references, bank references, and financial statement review for significant accounts. Credit limits by customer — reviewed annually and adjusted for changes in customer financial condition — prevent excessive concentration of receivables in vulnerable buyers.\n\nPayment performance tracking — monitoring debtor days by customer, escalating overdue accounts systematically, and suspending credit for persistent late payers — is essential for EU export trading companies. The difficulty of recovering overdue international debts (legal costs, jurisdictional uncertainty, enforcement challenges) justifies more conservative credit management than equivalent domestic trade relationships.'
