        content: 'Fee setting is the most consequential financial decision for EU childcare businesses, and the most commonly miscalculated. Many nursery operators set fees by benchmarking against competitors rather than calculating their own cost of care, resulting in fees that are competitive in the market but insufficient to cover operational costs — particularly in high-labour-cost EU urban markets.\n\nTrue cost of care calculation requires: staff costs per child place (ratio-compliant staffing cost divided by available place capacity), premises cost per place (rent/mortgage, rates, maintenance, utilities), food and consumables per child per day, management overhead per place, compliance and insurance costs per place, and a target operating margin. In most EU urban markets, this calculation yields a true cost of €40–€70 per full-time equivalent child per day.\n\nEU member state government childcare funding rates — the per-child amounts paid to providers for funded hours — frequently fall below the true cost of care, creating a structural funding gap. Nurseries that accept funded places without understanding the full cost implications may be operating funded sessions at a loss while private-fee sessions cross-subsidise the deficit. Explicit cost accounting by funding type reveals whether this cross-subsidy is occurring.\n\nFee increases are psychologically difficult for nursery operators because childcare is personally significant to parents. However, nurseries that fail to increase fees at least in line with staff cost inflation experience progressive margin erosion. Annual fee reviews with adequate notice (typically four to eight weeks) are minimum practice; market positioning reviews every two to three years assess whether fee level appropriately reflects service quality.'
